pchangeofhands.pchangeofhand:
The handwriting is uniform, characterized by right-sloping finely rounded letters with carefully executed, uniform "feet". 
Some distinctive/ancient features: 
-  ሎ has sometimes the 7th order marker attached directly at the body of the letter, without horizontal stroke (fol. 1va l.11); 
- መ, ዐ have angular shape. 
- መ has the loops not separated and the top is slightly  slanted to the left;
- ኴ has the loop marking the 5th order open (fol. 15rb l.13);
- the numerals are written in red without dashes above and below (e.g., fol. 14ra l.1), or in black with red and black dashes above and below (e.g., fols. 40ra l.15, 104ra l.7);
- ፬ is triangular and oriented downwards (e.g., fol. 89rb l.11); 
- ፮ has the loop open, looking like “compressed” ፯ (e.g., fol. 119vb l.11).

ppunctuations.ppunctuation:
Executed: not quite regularly;
Usage: not always logical.
Dividers:
I. Colon.  
II. Four dot asterisk (e.g. fols.: 18va, ls. 11, 18, 30; 19 ra, ls. 16, 24; 20rb, ls. 5, 12, 27; 132rb, l.2);
nine dot asterisk (used throughout the text).
Sentence dividers are accompanied by the paragraph signs, on the left from the text column and between the two columns (used throughout the Ms.).
III. Doubled nine dot asterisks, with lines in between (esp. fols.: 21rb, l.31; 21va, l.8; 124ra, ls. 8, 19; 144va, l.22; 144vb, l.25);
nine dot asterisks, connected with lines (esp. fol. 126rb, l.8);
four dot asterisks, connected with lines (esp. fols.:  131vb, l.29; 135vb, l.17);
Chain of black lines and red and black dots (e.g. fols. 1rab, l.1; 1ra, ls. 16-17; 12rb, ls. 20, 28; 15rb, l. 15; 16vb, l.31;  17ra, l.1; 18vb, l.7; 19vb, l.21; 53rb, l.11; 63vb, l.1; 89ra, ls. 30-31; 89rb, l.1; 109vb, l.1; 126rb, l.8; 150rb, l.25);
Crux ansata with coronis, marking the beginning of each new text (used thoughout the Ms.).
